  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Mr Wegg (who had had nothing else in his mind for several nights) took off his spectacles with an air of bland surprise."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘And I hope you’ll like it, Wegg.’"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘Thank you, sir,’ returned that reticent individual. ‘I hope it may prove so. On all accounts, I am sure.’ (This, as a philanthropic aspiration.)"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘What do you think,’ said Mr Boffin, ‘of not keeping a stall, Wegg?’"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘I think, sir,’ replied Wegg, ‘that I should like to be shown the gentleman prepared to make it worth my while!’"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘Here he is,’ said Mr Boffin."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Mr Wegg was going to say, My Benefactor, and had said My Bene, when a grandiloquent change came over him."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘No, Mr Boffin, not you sir. Anybody but you. Do not fear, Mr Boffin, that I shall contaminate the premises which your gold has bought, with <em>my</em> lowly pursuits. I am aware, sir, that it would not become me to carry on my little traffic under the windows of your mansion. I have already thought of that, and taken my measures. No need to be bought out, sir. Would Stepney Fields be considered intrusive? If not remote enough, I can go remoter. In the words of the poet’s song, which I do not quite remember:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "blockquote",
    "innerHtml": "<p>   Thrown on the wide world, doom’d to wander and roam,\n   Bereft of my parents, bereft of a home,\n   A stranger to something and what’s his name joy,\n   Behold little Edmund the poor Peasant boy.</p>"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "——And equally,’ said Mr Wegg, repairing the want of direct application in the last line, ‘behold myself on a similar footing!’"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘Now, Wegg, Wegg, Wegg,’ remonstrated the excellent Boffin. ‘You are too sensitive.’"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘I know I am, sir,’ returned Wegg, with obstinate magnanimity. ‘I am acquainted with my faults. I always was, from a child, too sensitive.’"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘But listen,’ pursued the Golden Dustman; ‘hear me out, Wegg. You have taken it into your head that I mean to pension you off.’"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘True, sir,’ returned Wegg, still with an obstinate magnanimity. ‘I am acquainted with my faults. Far be it from me to deny them. I <em>have</em> taken it into my head.’"
  },
