  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Was it the speciality of Mr and Mrs Lammle, or does it ever obtain with other loving couples? In these matrimonial dialogues they never addressed each other, but always some invisible presence that appeared to take a station about midway between them. Perhaps the skeleton in the cupboard comes out to be talked to, on such domestic occasions?"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘I have never seen any money in the house,’ said Mrs Lammle to the skeleton, ‘except my own annuity. That I swear.’"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘You needn’t take the trouble of swearing,’ said Mr Lammle to the skeleton; ‘once more, it doesn’t matter. You never turned your annuity to so good an account.’"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘Good an account! In what way?’ asked Mrs Lammle."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘In the way of getting credit, and living well,’ said Mr Lammle. Perhaps the skeleton laughed scornfully on being intrusted with this question and this answer; certainly Mrs Lammle did, and Mr Lammle did."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘And what is to happen next?’ asked Mrs Lammle of the skeleton."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘Smash is to happen next,’ said Mr Lammle to the same authority."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "After this, Mrs Lammle looked disdainfully at the skeleton—but without carrying the look on to Mr Lammle—and drooped her eyes. After that, Mr Lammle did exactly the same thing, and drooped <em>his</em> eyes. A servant then entering with toast, the skeleton retired into the closet, and shut itself up."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘Sophronia,’ said Mr Lammle, when the servant had withdrawn. And then, very much louder: ‘Sophronia!’"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘Well?’"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘Attend to me, if you please.’ He eyed her sternly until she did attend, and then went on. ‘I want to take counsel with you. Come, come; no more trifling. You know our league and covenant. We are to work together for our joint interest, and you are as knowing a hand as I am. We shouldn’t be together, if you were not. What’s to be done? We are hemmed into a corner. What shall we do?’"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘Have you no scheme on foot that will bring in anything?’"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Mr Lammle plunged into his whiskers for reflection, and came out hopeless: ‘No; as adventurers we are obliged to play rash games for chances of high winnings, and there has been a run of luck against us.’"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "She was resuming, ‘Have you nothing—’ when he stopped her."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘We, Sophronia. We, we, we.’"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘Have we nothing to sell?’"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘Deuce a bit. I have given a Jew a bill of sale on this furniture, and he could take it to-morrow, to-day, now. He would have taken it before now, I believe, but for Fledgeby.’"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘What has Fledgeby to do with him?’"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘Knew him. Cautioned me against him before I got into his claws. Couldn’t persuade him then, in behalf of somebody else.’"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘Do you mean that Fledgeby has at all softened him towards you?’"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘Us, Sophronia. Us, us, us.’"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘Towards us?’"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘I mean that the Jew has not yet done what he might have done, and that Fledgeby takes the credit of having got him to hold his hand.’"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘Do you believe Fledgeby?’"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘Sophronia, I never believe anybody. I never have, my dear, since I believed you. But it looks like it.’"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Having given her this back-handed reminder of her mutinous observations to the skeleton, Mr Lammle rose from table—perhaps, the better to conceal a smile, and a white dint or two about his nose—and took a turn on the carpet and came to the hearthrug."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘If we could have packed the brute off with Georgiana;—but however; that’s spilled milk.’"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "As Lammle, standing gathering up the skirts of his dressing-gown with his back to the fire, said this, looking down at his wife, she turned pale and looked down at the ground. With a sense of disloyalty upon her, and perhaps with a sense of personal danger—for she was afraid of him—even afraid of his hand and afraid of his foot, though he had never done her violence—she hastened to put herself right in his eyes."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘If we could borrow money, Alfred—’"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘Beg money, borrow money, or steal money. It would be all one to us, Sophronia,’ her husband struck in."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘—Then, we could weather this?’"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘No doubt. To offer another original and undeniable remark, Sophronia, two and two make four.’"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "But, seeing that she was turning something in her mind, he gathered up the skirts of his dressing-gown again, and, tucking them under one arm, and collecting his ample whiskers in his other hand, kept his eye upon her, silently."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘It is natural, Alfred,’ she said, looking up with some timidity into his face, ‘to think in such an emergency of the richest people we know, and the simplest.’"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘Just so, Sophronia.’"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘The Boffins.’"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘Just so, Sophronia.’"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘Is there nothing to be done with them?’"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘What is there to be done with them, Sophronia?’"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "She cast about in her thoughts again, and he kept his eye upon her as before."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘Of course I have repeatedly thought of the Boffins, Sophronia,’ he resumed, after a fruitless silence; ‘but I have seen my way to nothing. They are well guarded. That infernal Secretary stands between them and—people of merit.’"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘If he could be got rid of?’ said she, brightening a little, after more casting about."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘Take time, Sophronia,’ observed her watchful husband, in a patronizing manner."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘If working him out of the way could be presented in the light of a service to Mr Boffin?’"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘Take time, Sophronia.’"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘We have remarked lately, Alfred, that the old man is turning very suspicious and distrustful.’"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘Miserly too, my dear; which is far the most unpromising for us. Nevertheless, take time, Sophronia, take time.’"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "She took time and then said:"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘Suppose we should address ourselves to that tendency in him of which we have made ourselves quite sure. Suppose my conscience—’"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘And we know what a conscience it is, my soul. Yes?’"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘Suppose my conscience should not allow me to keep to myself any longer what that upstart girl told me of the Secretary’s having made a declaration to her. Suppose my conscience should oblige me to repeat it to Mr Boffin.’"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘I rather like that,’ said Lammle."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘Suppose I so repeated it to Mr Boffin, as to insinuate that my sensitive delicacy and honour—’"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘Very good words, Sophronia.’"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘—As to insinuate that <em>our</em> sensitive delicacy and honour,’ she resumed, with a bitter stress upon the phrase, ‘would not allow us to be silent parties to so mercenary and designing a speculation on the Secretary’s part, and so gross a breach of faith towards his confiding employer. Suppose I had imparted my virtuous uneasiness to my excellent husband, and he had said, in his integrity, “Sophronia, you must immediately disclose this to Mr Boffin.”’"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘Once more, Sophronia,’ observed Lammle, changing the leg on which he stood, ‘I rather like that.’"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘You remark that he is well guarded,’ she pursued. ‘I think so too. But if this should lead to his discharging his Secretary, there would be a weak place made.’"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘Go on expounding, Sophronia. I begin to like this very much.’"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘Having, in our unimpeachable rectitude, done him the service of opening his eyes to the treachery of the person he trusted, we shall have established a claim upon him and a confidence with him. Whether it can be made much of, or little of, we must wait—because we can’t help it—to see. Probably we shall make the most of it that is to be made.’"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘Probably,’ said Lammle."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘Do you think it impossible,’ she asked, in the same cold plotting way, ‘that you might replace the Secretary?’"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘Not impossible, Sophronia. It might be brought about. At any rate it might be skilfully led up to.’"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "She nodded her understanding of the hint, as she looked at the fire. ‘Mr Lammle,’ she said, musingly: not without a slight ironical touch: ‘Mr Lammle would be so delighted to do anything in his power. Mr Lammle, himself a man of business as well as a capitalist. Mr Lammle, accustomed to be intrusted with the most delicate affairs. Mr Lammle, who has managed my own little fortune so admirably, but who, to be sure, began to make his reputation with the advantage of being a man of property, above temptation, and beyond suspicion.’"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Mr Lammle smiled, and even patted her on the head. In his sinister relish of the scheme, as he stood above her, making it the subject of his cogitations, he seemed to have twice as much nose on his face as he had ever had in his life."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "He stood pondering, and she sat looking at the dusty fire without moving, for some time. But, the moment he began to speak again she looked up with a wince and attended to him, as if that double-dealing of hers had been in her mind, and the fear were revived in her of his hand or his foot."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘It appears to me, Sophronia, that you have omitted one branch of the subject. Perhaps not, for women understand women. We might oust the girl herself?’"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Mrs Lammle shook her head. ‘She has an immensely strong hold upon them both, Alfred. Not to be compared with that of a paid secretary.’"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘But the dear child,’ said Lammle, with a crooked smile, ‘ought to have been open with her benefactor and benefactress. The darling love ought to have reposed unbounded confidence in her benefactor and benefactress.’"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Sophronia shook her head again."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘Well! Women understand women,’ said her husband, rather disappointed. ‘I don’t press it. It might be the making of our fortune to make a clean sweep of them both. With me to manage the property, and my wife to manage the people—Whew!’"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Again shaking her head, she returned: ‘They will never quarrel with the girl. They will never punish the girl. We must accept the girl, rely upon it.’"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘Well!’ cried Lammle, shrugging his shoulders, ‘so be it: only always remember that we don’t want her.’"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘Now, the sole remaining question is,’ said Mrs Lammle, ‘when shall I begin?’"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘You cannot begin too soon, Sophronia. As I have told you, the condition of our affairs is desperate, and may be blown upon at any moment.’"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘I must secure Mr Boffin alone, Alfred. If his wife was present, she would throw oil upon the waters. I know I should fail to move him to an angry outburst, if his wife was there. And as to the girl herself—as I am going to betray her confidence, she is equally out of the question.’"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘It wouldn’t do to write for an appointment?’ said Lammle."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘No, certainly not. They would wonder among themselves why I wrote, and I want to have him wholly unprepared.’"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘Call, and ask to see him alone?’ suggested Lammle."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘I would rather not do that either. Leave it to me. Spare me the little carriage for to-day, and for to-morrow (if I don’t succeed to-day), and I’ll lie in wait for him.’"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "It was barely settled when a manly form was seen to pass the windows and heard to knock and ring. ‘Here’s Fledgeby,’ said Lammle. ‘He admires you, and has a high opinion of you. I’ll be out. Coax him to use his influence with the Jew. His name is Riah, of the House of Pubsey and Co.’ Adding these words under his breath, lest he should be audible in the erect ears of Mr Fledgeby, through two keyholes and the hall, Lammle, making signals of discretion to his servant, went softly up stairs."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘Mr Fledgeby,’ said Mrs Lammle, giving him a very gracious reception, ‘so glad to see you! My poor dear Alfred, who is greatly worried just now about his affairs, went out rather early. Dear Mr Fledgeby, do sit down.’"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Dear Mr Fledgeby did sit down, and satisfied himself (or, judging from the expression of his countenance, _dis_satisfied himself) that nothing new had occurred in the way of whisker-sprout since he came round the corner from the Albany."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘Dear Mr Fledgeby, it was needless to mention to you that my poor dear Alfred is much worried about his affairs at present, for he has told me what a comfort you are to him in his temporary difficulties, and what a great service you have rendered him.’"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘Oh!’ said Mr Fledgeby."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘Yes,’ said Mrs Lammle."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘I didn’t know,’ remarked Mr Fledgeby, trying a new part of his chair, ‘but that Lammle might be reserved about his affairs.’"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘Not to me,’ said Mrs Lammle, with deep feeling."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘Oh, indeed?’ said Fledgeby."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘Not to me, dear Mr Fledgeby. I am his wife.’"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘Yes. I—I always understood so,’ said Mr Fledgeby."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘And as the wife of Alfred, may I, dear Mr Fledgeby, wholly without his authority or knowledge, as I am sure your discernment will perceive, entreat you to continue that great service, and once more use your well-earned influence with Mr Riah for a little more indulgence? The name I have heard Alfred mention, tossing in his dreams, <em>is</em> Riah; is it not?’"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘The name of the Creditor is Riah,’ said Mr Fledgeby, with a rather uncompromising accent on his noun-substantive. ‘Saint Mary Axe. Pubsey and Co.’"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘Oh yes!’ exclaimed Mrs Lammle, clasping her hands with a certain gushing wildness. ‘Pubsey and Co.!’"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘The pleading of the feminine—’ Mr Fledgeby began, and there stuck so long for a word to get on with, that Mrs Lammle offered him sweetly, ‘Heart?’"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘No,’ said Mr Fledgeby, ‘Gender—is ever what a man is bound to listen to, and I wish it rested with myself. But this Riah is a nasty one, Mrs Lammle; he really is.’"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘Not if <em>you</em> speak to him, dear Mr Fledgeby.’"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘Upon my soul and body he is!’ said Fledgeby."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘Try. Try once more, dearest Mr Fledgeby. What is there you cannot do, if you will!’"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘Thank you,’ said Fledgeby, ‘you’re very complimentary to say so. I don’t mind trying him again, at your request. But of course I can’t answer for the consequences. Riah is a tough subject, and when he says he’ll do a thing, he’ll do it.’"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘Exactly so,’ cried Mrs Lammle, ‘and when he says to you he’ll wait, he’ll wait.’"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "(‘She is a devilish clever woman,’ thought Fledgeby. ‘I didn’t see that opening, but she spies it out and cuts into it as soon as it’s made.’)"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘In point of fact, dear Mr Fledgeby,’ Mrs Lammle went on in a very interesting manner, ‘not to affect concealment of Alfred’s hopes, to you who are so much his friend, there is a distant break in his horizon.’"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "This figure of speech seemed rather mysterious to Fascination Fledgeby, who said, ‘There’s a what in his—eh?’"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘Alfred, dear Mr Fledgeby, discussed with me this very morning before he went out, some prospects he has, which might entirely change the aspect of his present troubles.’"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘Really?’ said Fledgeby."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘O yes!’ Here Mrs Lammle brought her handkerchief into play. ‘And you know, dear Mr Fledgeby—you who study the human heart, and study the world—what an affliction it would be to lose position and to lose credit, when ability to tide over a very short time might save all appearances.’"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘Oh!’ said Fledgeby. ‘Then you think, Mrs Lammle, that if Lammle got time, he wouldn’t burst up?—To use an expression,’ Mr Fledgeby apologetically explained, ‘which is adopted in the Money Market.’"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘Indeed yes. Truly, truly, yes!’"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘That makes all the difference,’ said Fledgeby. ‘I’ll make a point of seeing Riah at once.’"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘Blessings on you, dearest Mr Fledgeby!’"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘Not at all,’ said Fledgeby. She gave him her hand. ‘The hand,’ said Mr Fledgeby, ‘of a lovely and superior-minded female is ever the repayment of a—’"
  },
  {
    "tag": "img",
    "innerHtml": "https://raw.githubusercontent.com/marvindanig/our-mutual-friend/master/assets/images/0535m.jpg"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": ""
  },
  {
    "tag": "hr",
    "innerHtml": ""
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘Noble action!’ said Mrs Lammle, extremely anxious to get rid of him."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘It wasn’t what I was going to say,’ returned Fledgeby, who never would, under any circumstances, accept a suggested expression, ‘but you’re very complimentary. May I imprint a—a one—upon it? Good morning!’"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘I may depend upon your promptitude, dearest Mr Fledgeby?’"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Said Fledgeby, looking back at the door and respectfully kissing his hand, ‘You may depend upon it.’"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "In fact, Mr Fledgeby sped on his errand of mercy through the streets, at so brisk a rate that his feet might have been winged by all the good spirits that wait on Generosity. They might have taken up their station in his breast, too, for he was blithe and merry. There was quite a fresh trill in his voice, when, arriving at the counting-house in St Mary Axe, and finding it for the moment empty, he trolled forth at the foot of the staircase: ‘Now, Judah, what are you up to there?’"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The old man appeared, with his accustomed deference."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘Halloa!’ said Fledgeby, falling back, with a wink. ‘You mean mischief, Jerusalem!’"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The old man raised his eyes inquiringly."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘Yes you do,’ said Fledgeby. ‘Oh, you sinner! Oh, you dodger! What! You’re going to act upon that bill of sale at Lammle’s, are you? Nothing will turn you, won’t it? You won’t be put off for another single minute, won’t you?’"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Ordered to immediate action by the master’s tone and look, the old man took up his hat from the little counter where it lay."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘You have been told that he might pull through it, if you didn’t go in to win, Wide-Awake; have you?’ said Fledgeby. ‘And it’s not your game that he should pull through it; ain’t it? You having got security, and there being enough to pay you? Oh, you Jew!’"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "The old man stood irresolute and uncertain for a moment, as if there might be further instructions for him in reserve."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘Do I go, sir?’ he at length asked in a low voice."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘Asks me if he is going!’ exclaimed Fledgeby. ‘Asks me, as if he didn’t know his own purpose! Asks me, as if he hadn’t got his hat on ready! Asks me, as if his sharp old eye—why, it cuts like a knife—wasn’t looking at his walking-stick by the door!’"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘Do I go, sir?’"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "‘Do you go?’ sneered Fledgeby. ‘Yes, you do go. Toddle, Judah!’"
  },
  {
    "tag": "hr",
    "innerHtml": ""
  },
  {
    "tag": "h4",
    "innerHtml": "Chapter 13"
  },
  {
    "tag": "h3",
    "innerHtml": "Give A Dog A Bad Name, And Hang Him"
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
    "innerHtml": "Fascination Fledgeby, left alone in the counting-house, strolled about with his hat on one side, whistling, and investigating the drawers, and prying here and there for any small evidences of his being cheated, but could find none. ‘Not his merit that he don’t cheat me,’ was Mr Fledgeby’s commentary delivered with a wink, ‘but my precaution.’ He then with a lazy grandeur asserted his rights as lord of Pubsey and Co. by poking his cane at the stools and boxes, and spitting in the fireplace, and so loitered royally to the window and looked out into the narrow street, with his small eyes just peering over the top of Pubsey and Co.‘s blind. As a blind in more senses than one, it reminded him that he was alone in the counting-house with the front door open. He was moving away to shut it, lest he should be injudiciously identified with the establishment, when he was stopped by some one coming to the door."
  },
  {
    "tag": "p",
